 ********** PLEASE NOTE: ****************************************************

 @{b}SCRIPT FAILS IMMEDIATELY WITH "IF MUST BE IN A COMMAND LINE" @{ub}

  One common problem I have found is that there are some hack or old versions
 of ICONX around that crash the script for what reason I do not know. It falls
 over at the first IF statement and is not the scripts fault, something about
 "IF must be in a command line". Load up the original ICONX file in the C:
 directory, supplied by commodore from 2.1 on and the script will work fine.


  When unpacking the archive, make sure the -a switch is set for LHA to unpack
 the protection bits. (The s-script bit must be set for most of these files)

 For instance, like this-   c:lha -x -M x -a Ram:ExtLister_18.lha

  In particular, the S directory scripts must have their script and executable
 Protection bits set!!! (The search button will not work for instance if this
 is not done.)

 ****************************************************************************

@ENDNODE

@NODE "Introduction"

                        Introduction
                        ------------

   FreeWare: ExtLister by Robbie Wegner Or Email-Ware, drop me a short line!

   rwegner@nor.com.au
   
   Warning: This is release Version 1.8 Use at your own risk!!!
  I will not be liable for any damages incurred in the use of these scripts
  in any way!

  I wanted to automatically make a list of my files that have extentions and
 link them to a default tool in an AmigaGuide document. This, such that
 when I click on a button for each file, a default tool will be loaded and the
 actual file given to the tool to display, edit, play, what ever!
 
  Not only that, but I wanted a script I could execute that would automatically
 update the Guide when I add or delete extention files from my hard drive.
 (Rather than reselect all the settings for the guide and manually create it
 again!)

  For instance List all #?.doc, #?.readme, #?.guide, #?.Txt files and be able
 to click on a button in the Guide and load any of these into an appropriate
 viewer such as the PD program MuchMore or Multiview and display them. I needed
 something like this because I keep all my documents with my programs, hence
 they are spread everywhere on my Hard drive and are hard to find. (easier to
 delete with their program and its files)

  You can do anything with a file extention, though for things like Picture
 files, there are better ways of making catalogues. Never the less you can
 use it to do things like picture extentions:

 #?.IFF
 #?.jpeg
 #?.Gif
 etc.

  You can then automaticaly load them into an appropriate viewer like ViewT;
 all with a single click of the button from within an AmigaGuide document.
 The same for Music files, instrument files etc. Anything with a file
 extention! Saves a lot of requestor clicking.

  Each type of extention file can have its own default tool, and can also have
 an extra function button to for instance, load an editing tool up and pass the
 file to it, or perhaps use as an unpack button for Lha files etc. The main one
 is used to view the file, and the other to load it into an editor, paint
 program, unpacker script, to move, copy or delete the file, etc.

 NOTE: Both the default tool and Extra Function default tool can have arguments
 as per normal. Enter them manually in the default tool string requestor at
 the Guides creation.

 Both can also use Dos Scripts as the default tool to do just about anything
 you want! So long as they can accept an argument for the extention files name
 and path using the ".KEY" Dos function to pass it to the script.

  One special script supplied with the program allows you to have a Floating
 toolbar to alter the function of the buttons on the fly. Depending on the
 selection in the tool bar, the button in the Amiga Guide will do different
 things to the listed files. See ExtDMCR file description in installation. Does
 Delete, Move, A Dos command or tool of your choice via a requestor or
 manual entry, Copy, and Rename at present.

  This is useful for finding files across your whole hard drive that may be
 doubled up or are in the wrong place, or are simply not needed any more
 and you did not know they were there.
 
  Using the floating tool bar, you can change the function of the buttons in
 the guide as the need arises to move, delete, or copy etc, as you look
 through the guide itself! Something difficult to do with a Directory
 utility when files are so wide spread. I find it particularly useful for
 keeping track of and managing files on my ZIP drive disk collection,
 especially in conjunction with the built in search feature in the Amiga Guide
 to find files on the collection.

 @{b}Searching for Extention files to make lists.@{ub} 

 You can search for extention types for each individual list by-

 -any extention type in the selected directory. (Selects all Extention files)

 -multiple extentions in one list using wildcards or the Dos OR switch and
 brackets. I.E.-

  (.readme|.doc|.guide|.readme)

 -or just one extention per list.     (Manual entry or by requestor)

 @{b}Searching the lists of Extention files in the AmigaGuide itself.@{ub}

  The generated AmigaGuides have a search facility built in that generates a
 new seperate AmigaGuide document with the search results. This new guide is
 fully functional like the main one and is saved in RAM: so you can move it
 and keep it. The next search overwrites the old one! The searches support 
 Dos wildcards E.G. "r#?d" would find all files an "r" and a "d" some where
 in the file name.

  There are also optional lists that are automatically
 generated for cross reference...
 
 -Directory ALL (DirAll)

 -Extention ALL (ExtAll)
 and..

 -All files found (THE WORKS!)

 ...to help you find files alphabetically in large lists....

 -by directory selection containing all extention types searched for in
  that directory choice only,

 -by extention type for all directory or device selections,

 -alphabetically, all listed files from all of the directories selected.

 @{b}AutoScript@{ub} 

  There is also an autoscript generated with each Guide made, that is a
 permanent self-contained script to update this particular guide when ever
 you wish. Simply by re-executing this customised autoscript, it will update
 the whole guide automatically, replacing the old one.
 (In case you add new extention files or delete old ones.) In fact the
 created AutoScript makes the actual guide in the first place, not the
 ExtLister script!! ExtLister simply collects the data for your selections
 and then appends the main Autoscript body file called SearchTail-Guide, onto
 that data.

 The Searchtail script then uses that data to create the guide and search for
 the extention files to list in the Guide. It is executed to make the initial
 Guide and can be moved and renamed after, so that you can update your Guide
 at any time in the future.

  If you add a few new sound samples to your collection for instance, simply
 execute the autoscript and the old guide will be updated complete with all
 of your original settings.

  These AutoScripts are where the real usefulness of ExtentionLister becomes
 evident.
  No need to reselect the same extentions, button names, default tools or
 directories again manually to update your old guide!

  Each guide gets its own Autoscript which you can rename to what you like
 and put where you like. It will only update that particular guide!

 @{b}AminetCDLister@{ub}

  There is an AminetCD Lister script to make customised guides with search,
 index lists, readmes and a Copy or unpack to RAM: button for each LHA file.
  If it is not a LHA file, the unpack button will view it if it is a .JPEG
 for instance or what ever.

  You can list across CDs. eg., all of the Utilities directories across all
 of your Aminet CD's so they are all listed in one guide. Thus you can then
 easily search for utility files off your whole Aminet CD collection all from
 within one single guide, using the built in search function; far qicker and
 more reliable than Aminets own horrible Guide search function.

  Using the ReadMe ALL list option then, it is easy to see where the latest
 version of a file is, as it lists every readme file found in your directory
 choices all in the one sorted list.

 @{b}Additional Scripts@{ub}

  There are a few extra scripts to do various things that I find useful and
 are closely related to Extention lister and what it is used for. check out
 the documents in this drawer for each one.


 @{b}HTML- World Wide Web output@{ub}

 This is still under construction, but I have included it anyway. Someone may
 find the current output useful for something :)

  At this stage I am not really sure of what these could be useful for. Perhaps
 your Home Page could contain a list of your Gif and JPEG files that are
 automatically updated with the Autoscript. If you add or delete Pics, just
 execute the autoscript to update the file lists and replace the old lists
 in your homepage.
 Since this format uses seperate files for the lists and Main page, you could
 set up a permanent page to link to these lists, but not use the front page
 that is made by the autoscript.

 So long as your Main page references the same files as the Autoscript main
 page (they don't change), you only need make a front end in your Home page
 and change the list files using the autoscript (just ignore the Main page that
 the autoscript makes).

 Confused? Me too!

  It ignores all of the default tool settings and simply makes a link to the
 file at this stage and has no search of course since it is multiplatform.
  The file that does all of the work is the SearchTail-HTML file (it has no
 icon) in the main drawer of Extlister. This is appended onto the data
 collected by the Extlister script to become the AutoScript. I have marked
 in the script where the headers and actual generated list output are made so
 you can alter it to your own needs.

 At the moment it only does a...

 <a Href="...........">linkfilename</a>

 ....type link at the moment.

 YOU MUST MAKE SURE YOU KNOW WHAT YOU ARE DOING WHEN YOU ALTER THE SCRIPTS!!
 I.E. a knowledge of HTML files would be a good place to start, and of DOS.


=============================================================================
  
  These scripts were done as an exercise to learn Amiga Dos. They are well
 commented for anyone interested in looking at what is possible with Dos and
 a few tricks, tips and problems that I have picked up in making them.

 WARNING: Because they would be so easy to tamper with, make sure that you
 only down load versions from a safe source such as AMINET!! 

  There are some sample guides generated by these scripts in the package.
 These will show you the layout. The extra DirALL, ExtALL and WORKS! lists are
 optional. There is also a sample AutoScript that will search your SYS: and
 WORK: partition if you have one, for documents of various kinds and generate
 a guide in RAM: for you to try out. It will function without installing
 anything, except the search button and the DMCR buttons in the guide will not
 work. It needs AskEnv in the C: Dir and the ExtListerSearch script in the S:
 Dir. DMCR needs ExtDMCR and ExtDMCR-Window in the s: Directory to work.
 The rest of the commands it uses are standard with Workbench 2.1 and above.


  DELETE THE SAMPLES TO SAVE HARDDRIVE SPACE AFTER YOU HAVE FINISHED LOOKING
 AT THEM !!!! They are not needed for the program!


