@ENDNODE

@NODE "Programed In"

                       Programed In Dos
                       ----------------


  These are Amiga Dos generators and using AskEnv for the GUI. No arexx.

  Don't laugh! It may have been better done in arexx or C, but I wanted to 
 learn more about Dos, and I certainly did that! This is my second large Dos
 program. The longest script I have written, prior to these, was about five
 lines. It gets along quite well really and I wish to thank Mark Constable
 for allowing me to watch over his shoulder to see just what is possible
 with Dos. It is a lot more powerful than I first thought.

  Even so, there are a few limitations that I have not been able to fix.
 See Things to fix in Problems.

  Anyone interested in converting it to C is welcome; would appreciate a
 mention if nothing else. Maybe use the Whatis libary and do away with the
 extentions all together.

  I would also like to mention the authors of "Mastering Amiga Dos" series,
 Mark Smiddy and Bruce Smith for their great books! Without them I would 
 not have made it past square one and cannot recommend them enough!

  I have tried as much as possible to explain the scripts with embedded
 comments so that you can play with them or alter them to your own needs.
  However, if you delete your hard drive through playing with these scripts,
 don't abuse me!!
 
  There are two parts to the script, the main one is the ExtLister script
 which you make your choices for the guides setup, and a SearchTail script
 that is appended onto the end of the data collected by the first script.

  This then becomes the AutoScript that actually makes the Guide. (ExtLister
 does not make the guide) The SearchTail script has no icon and is in the
 main directory with ExtLister. The AutoScript is then executed to make the 
 actual Amiga Guide.

  ExtLister is a grander scaled up version of an older dos script I was
 working on called DocLister, but is not limited to document files
 anymore!
 
  Thanks to Graeme Belle for the ideas for added features and bug reports.
 He is using the Guide lists to play his instrument sounds in the Bars and
 Pipes window to find the one he wants far quicker than any other.
 (much quicker than loading them into a player manually to hear them.)
 
  Thanks also to Bob from Bobs BBS in Lismore NSW Australia for doing a lot of
 preliminary testing for me. Ta Bob!

 Finally thanks again to Mark Constable for helping me with some problems with
 the scripts.
 

 ===========================================================================
 
  Note: If you do not like the beep and screen flash, the line is indicated in
 the "SearchTail" script (it has no icon) and in the AminetCDLister script.
 Just load the scripts into a text editor and delete that line and save the
 script back again. It is towards the end of each script. The SearchTail is
 added onto the data file that the ExtLister script makes to create your
 AutoScript file. It does the actual search and creation of the Guide itsself.

 Look for these lines-

 ;******** Delete the next line if you do not like the Beep and screen flash. **

 Eval 7 lformat "%c"

 ;******************************************************************************


 Do not use a wordprocessor to edit these files !!!
 
 ==============================================================================


@ENDNODE

@NODE "Requirements"
 
                        Requirements:
                        -------------
 
  WorkBench 2.1 and above! Due mostly to the List command Lformat output. It
 needs the "%<xx>.<yy>N" formatting option to ensure the lists are neat and
 tidy. Also the %E and %M. These are only available with 2.1 and on. 

  You will need AskEnv in your C: directory, ENV: S: and RAM: must exist.
 And of course you will need MultiView or the AmigaGuide program itself to
 look at the generated Guides. MuchMore is used in some of the Aminet CD 
 search scripts.
 
 The rest are quite standard commands. ( ED is needed for the the search
 functions ??? )

  All C: commands needed are made resident (add) and removed afterwards to
 check their existance, and speed things up.

 AskEnv came out on Fish disk 891. I have included the LHA file here as it
 is not available on Aminet that I can find. (I hope the author does not mind!)
  Its quite old now, but was the only suitable thing I could find for the
 job that was quite small and interfaced to Dos. MUI is too big and not
 everyone likes using it.


 There is an S drawer with some scripts in them. Use the install script or
 copy them to your S: directory (it will set the script bits for you).
  Several are search scripts that must be there for the search functions for
 the Aminet and standard guides. Check that the script and executable bits are
 set, or they will not work!


  A fair wack of RAM to read large guides with the ALL and THE WORKS! lists
 switched on.


  Aminet Guides generated can be very large, but they compress up to 90%
 for storage !!!
  If you use something like ARCHANDLER, you can keep them compressed and
 read them through this. Aminet6.Guide compresses from 1.5 meg down to
 137 k for instance. Thus you can easily store these guides on your
 hard drive for your whole Aminet CD collection. You still need a fair amount
 of memory to uncrunch them and use them though!




 *********TIPS TO KEEP MEMORY USAGE DOWN! ********************************

  When making some of these guides, they can be quite large, especially the
 AminetCD ones! To keep them to a minimal size, select things like the
 default tools or scripts using assigns like C: and S: rather than-

 SYS:c/muchmore or SYS:s/ExtLHA-X

 or worse-

 WORKBENCH:c/muchmore or WORKBENCH:s/ExtLHA-X

  These default tools and paths to your files are repeated hundreds of
 times in just one guide! By keeping the paths to a minimum, the over all 
 guides will be much smaller; also the paths to the files. Make assigns for
 your documents and pictures and use those instead of the full path.

 PICS:  instead of WORK:Graphics/pictures/  for instance.
 DOCS:  instead of WORKBENCH:Documents/

  Use the device names instead of Volume names

 DH0: instead of WORKBENCH: for instance.

 @{b}NOTE: Do not use CD0: for the AminetCD lister though! The Guide will not
 know which CD to get your files from! Always go back to the volume name,
 especially when listing across CDs! @{ub}


 ************************************************************************

@ENDNODE

@NODE "Problems" 

                         Problems
                         --------
  When unpacking this file, make sure the -a switch is set for LHA.
  This is so the script files will get their proper protection bits set.
 Mostly the Script and Executable bits must be set for all of the scripts
 or they will not execute. For instance, if the search feature does not work,
 this may be a pretty good reason why! The small install script will set
 the file bits for you and copy the files to your S: directory (it is the
 only reason it is there, specificly for this problem). 

 @{b}SCRIPT FAILS IMMEDIATELY WITH "IF MUST BE IN A COMMAND LINE" @{ub}

  One problem I have found is that there are some hack or old versions of
 ICONX around that crash the script for what reason I do not know. It falls
 over at the first IF statement and is not the scripts fault, something about
 "IF must be in a command line". Load up the original ICONX file in the C:
 directory, supplied by commodore from 2.1 on and the script will work fine.

 @{b}SCRIPT FAILS WITH "AskEnv can not open its window" @{ub}

 AskEnv's window is set to 241 high. NTSC high res is ok, but any lower
 resolutions will fail because the window is not high enough or may not be
 wide enough!

 @{b}NO SPACES IN FILE OR DIRECTORY NAMES @{ub}

  AmigaGuide documents will not tolerate spaces in file names or directories
 for the "System" function (a Dos command line can be executed from within
 a guide using this command). This is to do with executing the default tools
 and giving them the extention files as an argument.

  Amigaguide will not allow extra quotation marks inside the button links to
 allow for the spaces in the file path or file name of either the default
 tool or the extention file. Escaping them does not work either!

  Sorry, no can do. The guide will be put together and look normal, except it
 will not load an extention file into the default tool if there is a space
 in the files path or name. All other file buttons should still work fine.

 You can however, put spaces in the customised button names and extra button
 names. Spaces obviously can be used to enter Arguments for the default
 tools, (just not the filename or its path!)

 If a button does not work, but loads the default tool and does not open the
 file, spaces in the Extention files path or name may be a good reason why!

 @{b}ASKENV FAILS AND SCRIPT CONTINUES ON@{ub}
 
 Do not use 020MathPatch on AskEnv. It stops it working for some reason!!


 @{b}DO NOT RENAME THE GUIDES AFTER CREATION@{ub}

  You must not rename the Guides, or the internal search function will not
 work! If you do, and cannot remember what it was originally called, an
 error will occur if you try to use the search button. The search script
 will then tell you what the guide was originally called so you can rename
 it back!

 @{b}MOVING THE GUIDE TO A DIFFERENT LOCATION OR RENAMING THE DIRECTORY ITS IN@{ub}

 If you do not wish to use the autoscript, then the generated Guides can be
 put where you like. However, the autoscript when executed, will generate a
 new Guide in the drawer where you originally choose to put it, and will not
 update the old one as such.

  For that reason, you should make sure that the place you choose to place
 the guide is its permanent home if you wish to use the Autoscripts to
 update the guide.

  If you rename any part of the path to the guide, the AutoScript will
 fail!

 (If you know what you are doing, edit the AutoScript to tell it the new path
 and or name of the Guide. It is the first line of the script and looks like
 this-

 SetEnv File <Guides path and name>

 Replace <Guides path and name> with the path and name of your guide.

 Eg- 

 SetEnv File WorkBench:Documents/Ext.Guide
 to-
 SetEnv File WorkBench:Documents/Document.Guide


 @{b}File Names are too long and are getting cut off.@{ub}

  The button width for the file names is currently set to 25. Unfortunately
 this cannot be set as a variable in the List command, thus cannot be
 dynamically adjusted. If you MUST have file names longer than 25 characters
 and need to see the whole name, alter the lines in the searchtail_guide
 script. A new value needs to be added in two places in the line.
 There are four such lines in the script that need to be changed- if you
 have trouble understanding what is required, you should not be attempting
 it in the first place!!! This is (part of) the line.......

 List $Selection all pat=#?$Ext LFormat " a{*"%-25.25N*" system *"Run $Ext1...

 - the part

 %-25.25N* 

 - needs to change to say

 %-30.30N*

 - to alter the script to do 30 character buttons!!

 If the characters are getting cut off, this will NOT cause any problems!
 Remember there are four such lines that need to be changed! Use the search
 and replace function in your text editor......DO NOT USE A WORD PROCESSOR!!!

 @{b}NON STANDARD FONTS @{ub}

  AskEnv Gui's is not font sensitive!! The button names are every where if the
 font is an unusual one! It was designed around topaz, but handles Xhelvetica
 11 fine if you have Magic Workbench.


 @{b}THINGS TO FIX: @{ub}

