2. When you get a new CD, adding say the Utilities directory to an existing
 AminetGuide of all of the Utilities directories across all of your CD's is
 a headache. But then so is creating a new one for all your CD's from scratch.
 This may have to be done in C. The Dos script is messy enough as it is!
  It may be easier to create a new one for the new CD, then manually add it
 into to old one. If you are using the ReadMe ALL list, you will have to
 somehow cut the old one out, add the new one, then sort it, then put it
 back! Hmmmm.

3. Floating Tool bar for DMCR keeps redrawing in the centre. I cannot get the
 window cordinates to reposition the window where it was last dragged to.
 How can you get the cordinates? Help!

4. Askenv does not activate the cursor in its windows when opened. Nor does
  it close the window with the carriage return when things are entered into
  windows that have other buttons and only one string requestor or that use
  a file function. It would have been a nice feature if there is only one
  string requestor, to allow the carraige return to end the window session.
  As in the Search function and rename function. Even better, a special key
  press to close the window such as Alt Return or Alt Q.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "Instalation"
  
                       Installation:
                       -------------
 @{b}S: and C: directory files.@{ub}

  There are two scripts to install and remove ExtentionLister files from your
 S: and C: directories on your hard drive. Some S: directory scripts, and
 Askenv, a HTML viewer and Muchmore in the C: directory. If the C: ones already
 exist, then it will not write over what is there. At removal, the S: directory
 scripts are removed and it will ask if you want to delete AskEnv, MoreText
 and MuchMore. MuchMore would be a good one to keep, the other two may not be
 of much use unless other programs are using them already.

  The install script will set the correct protection bits if you do not use
 the -a switch for LHA. It will then copy the scripts to the S: directory.
 This is the only reason for the install scripts inclusion is to set these
 file bits!

 If you wish to use the extra Tools needed for the Aminet CD script to "Unpack"
 the files in the AminetGuides, then you will need to find and copy them to
 your C: directory yourself. (Not all of the Aminet files are LHA files, and you
 will need these tools to display them or what ever) See manual installation
 below for S: dir, the "ExtAmi" script. These tools are in the Tools
 directory on your Aminet CD's.

 @{b}ExtLister drawer.@{ub}

 The ExtLister drawer can be put anywhere, but make sure its internal
 structure remains unchanged. This is because the scripts look in the
 current directory for icons and for the "SearchTail" file for your new
 AutoScript. The sample guides drawer and its contents however, can be deleted
 when you are finished looking at it, it is not needed for the program. You
 will save about a meg of space.
 
 If you do not like the guide icon, replace it in the Icon drawer.
 Rename the new one the same as the old one! GuideIcon.info 
 
 @{b}The AutoScript file (Once made by the Extlister script) @{ub}

  The AutoScript file, once it has been created by the "ExtLister" script,
 can be renamed to what you like and put anywhere. It is made in RAM:

  The guide it updates must not be renamed or moved, or it will not be updated
 at a later date. Instead, a new one will be made where the old one use to be
 if you do.
  The Guide is given its icon when first created. The autoscript assumes that
 there is an icon there and does not update it. Hence if you delete the
 icon or move the original guide, the autoscript will not give the new guide
 an icon!! Because the auto script does not need to give the guide an icon,
 it can be fully self contained and be put anywhere and called anything.
 

 @{b}Manual installation and description of files in S directory.@{ub}

1. S dir files. (Do show all in the ExtentionLister drawer to see it)
  Just copy the files you want to your S: directory. Some are search scripts
 and must be there for your search buttons in the guides to work.

 ExtAmiSearch, ExtListerSearch, ExtAmiIndex are all search scripts. The Ami
 ones being for the ExtAminet script generated Guides. 

 The other files for the S: directory are as described below.


 1) The ExtLha-View file is a script to view LHA files. Set this as a default
  tool to view #?.LHA files. You will need LHA in the C: directory.


 2) The ExtLha-X file is a script to unpack Lha files to RAM: Set this as your
  Extra button default tool for .LHA files and you can unpack your lha files to
  RAM: from with-in the guides. You will need LHA in the C: directory.


 3) The ExtLZX-X and ExtLZX-View are the LZX versions like the LHA ones.
  You will need LZX in the C: directory.


 4) ExtAmi is the script used for the UnPack buttons in the AminetCD lists. If
  it detects that the file is not a packed one, it will for example, attempt to
  view it if it is a Jpeg using VT (ViewTech) or copy it to RAM: if it is a RUN
  file (Like selfextracting files) or an executable. It currently handles:

  .lha, .lzh, .lzx, .anim, .jpg, .dms, .txt, .gif, .run, .exe and .mpg files

   The .exe and .run files are simply copied to RAM: rather than executed.

   If it is a .dms file, You are asked first if you wish to automatically
  unpack it to DF0:

   Note: that it also will unpack LZX files (Aminet may be converting to LZX
   in the future). 

   NOTE: There is an aditional script called "FindNewFilesAmiCD" that will
   search an Aminet CD for extentions and list the ones the "ExtAmi" script
   does not cater for. It is in the additional scripts drawer!

 
   All extra Tools to view files like JPEGS and anims are on the Aminet CD
  in the tools directory. You will need:

  mpeg_player, VT (ViewTech), BigAnim, LHA, LZX, DMS and MuchMore

  Copy these to your C: Directory. (I find CD's are far too prone to crashing
 the machine and like to minimise access to them as much as possible. It is
 also faster off your hard drive.)

 ExtAmi can be used as a multipurpose default tool for other things as well,
 not just for the aminet CDs.

 5) ExtCopy is a small script to copy your files to a destination. If the
 Variable $CopyDestination does not exist, then a requestor will pop up and
 ask you for a destination. Once the variable is set, The script will not
 ask for a destination again until "ENV:CopyDestination" variable is
 deleted. All other copy buttons will use that variable while ever it exists!

 It will also copy the files icon if it can find one!

@{b} A "Reset Move\Copy Destination" button will be automatically put at the top
 of any file lists using the ExtCopy or ExtMove scripts, provided you set the
 default tool to either S:ExtMove, or S:ExtCopy. Sys:s/ExtCopy for instance
 will not work.@{ub}
  Clicking the reset button will delete the variable. On the next use of a
 file button, a requestor will pop up asking for a new destination.

  If you make a mistake and the reset buttons do not appear, a simple script in
 the Additional Scripts drawer called "DeleteCopyDest" will delete the variable
 to reset the destination if you do not know how to do it manually. The next
 copy button you use will then bring up a requestor for you to reset the
 destination to something new.


 6) ExtMove is the same as ExtCopy, except it will move the File and its icon if
 one is found. It works the same way by setting a variable called 
 MoveDestination for the destination to move the files to.

 7) ExtListFiles is a simple script to make a list of what files you select
  from the guide. This is usefull for making a list of various files to then
  alter later in a text editor. You can make a Dos script out of it to, for
  instance, do various things to the list of files it contains.
   It creates a file in RAM: called FileList. It has the Path and file name
  of the selected files you click on in the guide. As long as this file exists,
  the script will keep adding onto the end of it. It never over writes the
  existing one.

 8) ExtRename is a simple script to rename files from within the AmigaGuide.
    If you alter the path to the file, it will act as a Move function and
    or "Move As" function if you alter the file name as well.

 9) Finally a small one called ExtDelete. Set this as the extra tool, and call
  the button "Delete". Use this to delete the extention file. Good for
  searching your hard drive for files that you don't want anymore. Read,
  listen or look at the file with the normal button, and if it is not
  wanted, delete it with an Extra tool button set to this script. It will
  ask first for confirmation before deleting the file. 

 10) ExtDMCR is the default tool for the floating Tool bar script called
  ExtDMCR-Window. (ExtDMCR-Window is not a tool, just a dos script!!! It
 sets a variable $DMCRFunction to what ever function is set in the window.)
 The Window script sets this variable for which script to use of the above
 scripts or a special Dos command mode-
 
  ExtMove, ExtCopy, ExtDelete, ExtRename or the special COMMAND.
 
  The ExtDMCR script checks what the variable $DMCFunction is set to and
  then initiates the correct script when you click on a file button in the
  Amiga Guide and gives it the file as an argument.

  Put simply, you can change the function of a button in the Amiga Guide on
 the fly, without making up a new guide each time. Once the function is
 set, all other DMCR buttons in the Amiga Guide lists will now do that same
 function until you set the function to something else!

  The special COMMAND allows you to enter a one line dos command and the listed
 Extention file will be appended as an argument onto the end of this in
 append mode. Or if you enter the variable $ExtFile manually in the Dos
 Command, where you enter it. When you click on buttons in the extention file
 lists from then on, this command will be carried out with the file of that
 button given as an argument in the variable $ExtFile.

  The manual entry could infact replace some of the other functions like
 copy, but since they are more complicated, I have included them for beginners
 who are not farmiliar with Dos.

 The idea is that you only need type the command once then apply it to as
 many of the listed files in the Amiga Guide as you like by clicking on the
 button in the guide. ExtDMCR looks after the rest for you.

  You can also use a requestor to select a default tool and once OK is
 clicked, that default tool will be used each time you use the DMCR buttons
 in the guide from then on thus allowing you to alter the default tool on
 the fly as well.

  Of course, the Main extention file button can use the ExtDMCR tool as well,
 not just the Extra funtion button in the file lists which also need not be
 called DMCR. You can give it what ever name you want in the Extra function
 button name at the guides creation.

  If the Tool bar is not open, the first time you click on a S:ExtDMCR tool 
 button in the Amiga Guide, the ExtDMCR-Window script will be run and the
 window opened. You need to select your function then click on OK then
 back on the Extention list button again to carry out that function! The first
 click will only open the window of the tool bar, not carry out an
 opperation.

  From then on, while ever the tool bar window is open, the Extention file
 buttons in the Guide will do what ever the tool bar function is set to 
 immediately when you click on them.
  The Tool bar can be dragged over to one side and left until you need to alter
 the function of the buttons in the guide again later. NOTE: Its Window must
 remain open for the ExtDMCR buttons in the guide to function!
 
   The ToolBar has "move to" and "copy to" destination requestors so that you
 can alter them as needed for the MOVE and COPY functions.

 @{b}NOTE: You must click OK after changing the destinations or the functions,
 and Dos Commands, other wise they will not be recognised or implimented!!@{ub}

  Sorry, it is not a true floating tool bar, if OK is clicked on, the
 toolbar is redrawn back in the center of the screen rather than where you
 have dragged it to last. The limitations of a Dos program I'm afraid.  
 

2. C directory files. (Do show all in the ExtentionLister drawer to see it)
  Copy AskEnv and MuchMore to your C: directory. MoreText is a very basic HTML
  viewer. Only copy that if you need it.

  NOTE: Make sure you are not copying old versions over newer ones!!

@ENDNODE


@NODE "Description"
 
                         Description:
                         ------------
 

  Using requestors, you choose the device or directories that you want
 to make a list of your extentions from. This can be repeated as many times as
 you like. Thus creating an index in the main Contents window of the finished
 guide, of all the devices & directories that you have choosen.
 This index will have buttons that take you to the extention types and cross
 reference DirALL, ExtALL and THE WORKS! lists if they have been chosen.

 You are then asked for the extention types to search for in each directory
 or device you have choosen and to give each its own default tool.
 e.g. (#?.IFF -> c:viewt, #?.doc -> c:muchmore,  etc.)

  If you select the Extra Button Tool, you will need to select a default tool
 for that as well and give it a button name. (default is "DMCR" and of course
 the default tool is the S:ExtDMCR tool script).


  The script will then search down through all the subdirectories of the
 selections you make to find these extentions and create link buttons to the
 actual files and their default tools.

  When selecting your devices or directories to search, it is pointless to
 select directories within previous selections, as you will only be doubling
 up on extention files that will be listed already.

  There is an extra script that makes guides off Aminet CD's and works much
 the same way as the ExtLister's only with less options (needs less). 

 OPTIONS.
 --------

 These options are selected when you first start ExtLister

 1. You can have the same extention types to search for in each directory
 choice, or different extention types for each directory choice.
  For instance if you are like me, and your documents and guides are spread
 every where, to find them on your partitions, you would use the same
 extention types to search for across all directories/devices.
 ie., find all guides, documents, texts, manuals etc in all directory
 choices.

  However, if you want to list your documents from your document directory
 and only pictures from your picture directory, then you would use the
 separate extention type for each directory selected to search in.
 No point looking for documents in the picture dir if there are none there
 and vice versa for the pictures.

 2. You can also have Directory "DirAll" lists that show all files found for just
 that directory selection.
  That is, All of the extention files of each type choosen from that directory
 selection only. This is created automatically if you select it, and is sorted.

 This is for if you know the name of the file and what directory its in, but
 not the extention type.

 3. If it is a "same extentions across all directories" guide you get a choice
 of adding extra Extention ALL lists. These list the files across all
 directories, for each separate extention. ie. All #?.readme files across all
 the directory/devices you have selected.
  This if you know the extention of the file, but not which directory or
 partition its in. This is created automatically if you select it, and is
 sorted. 

 4. At the end of the main list, you can have a "THE WORKS!" button, listing
 all the extentions of each type you have chosen for every device or directory
 that you have choosen. This is created automatically if you select it, and is
 sorted of course, as they all are.

  This list is if you do not know a files extention or which dir or partition
 its on. Just its name and you want an alphabetical listing of everything.
 
 5. You are asked if you want customised Index button names for the extention
 lists. This allows you to give your own name to the extention buttons in the
 main index. By default it is set to the extention type. eg ".Doc" or
 ".readme" etc. But you could have "Documents" or "ReadMe Docs". These names
 can have spaces in them.

 6. You can also assign an extra button to each extention file in the list.
 This button can have a different tool for doing alternate things to the
 extention file.
  Thus you could have MuchMore to display a document as the normal button,
 and CygnusEd set as the extra function button to edit the document file.

 Note: These extra buttons are optional for each extention type in the same
 guide. Later when setting the extention type and its tools, if you do not
 want to select an extra tool for a particular extention type, just un-check
 the tick box. This will tell it not to give that extention type an extra
 button tool. This does not affect your other extention choices and their
 extra tool.

  Also, at that time, you will be asked for a name for this extra
 button to give it some meaning to you later. If you ignore this it will
 default to "DMCR". Each Extra button tool can have a different name for each
 extention type.

 7. The lists of extention files can have the directory path to each file, so
 you can find them. You can have path and file name, or just the Path, or
 nothing at all, or Files comment or date. You can also add the files size in
 the listing using a tick box. This is in addition to the previous
 selection.

 8. For the autoscripts to update the guide properly, you must tell the
 script where the new guides permanent home will be, so that it can find it
 to update it.
 When the ExtLister script is finished, it will automatically generate your
 new guide here by executing the AutoScript itself.

 9. You will need to give your guide a name. This must be its permanent name
 for the search function to work. It does not matter if the guide is moved,
 the search will still work, but if the guide is renamed, it won't.
 (The search function gets the name of the guide to search from with in the
 guide itself. Other wise the search script will not know which Amiga Guide 
 it has to search in!)

  If the Guides file name has been changed, the search script will fail and
 tell you what it was originally called, so you can rename it back!
 
 @{b}-If you realy must rename the guide, edit the guide itself and change the
 name in the Search button link. It would help a lot if you knew what you
 were doing to do this!

 NOTE: There is a "." and a number appended to the end of the guides name in
 this button link, DO NOT REMOVE OR ALTER THIS NUMBER or the search will not
 function properly, if at all! @{ub}
 You will also have to alter the path and file name in the Auto script for it
 to find and update the guide with its new name. (First line of the
 autoscript)

 10. The "No RAM: Path" is to give the script an alternate place to make
 the Amiga Guide other than RAM: if you are short of memory. It can be set to
 your Hard drive, Zip drive, what ever. By default, it is set to RAM: if you
 do not enter anything in the string box either manually or by using the
 requestor. 
 
@ENDNODE


@NODE "Instructions"

                       Instructions:
                       -------------
 
  Start the script ExtLister and you will be presented with a GUI window.
 
 This is where all of the main layout settings for the guide are.

 1. The first box decides if you want separate extentions for each directory
   choice you have.

 2. If you want Directory All lists.

 3. If you have selected "same extentions for each directory", you can
   select Extention All lists to be added.
 
 4. If you want a "The Works!" list or not.

 5. If you want to customise the extention button names in the contents window.
 
 6. If you want an extra button in the file lists, for an aditional tool.



 (Just tick the boxes for yes and un-tick them for no for each choice)



 7. and finally whether you want in your extention lists-

    -Path and File name
    -Just Path
    -or nothing
    -Comment
    -Date

  -via a cycle gadget; then tick the File size box if you want the files size
  added.

 8. You will be asked for a name for the guide and a path for where it is
 to be stored.

 10. If you are short of RAM, select an alternate place to make the guide
 using the "No RAM: Path" requestor. The entry must end in a ":" or a "/".


 Click on OK when you are happy with the settings. (If you do not
  understand what some of these mean see @{" Detailed Description " Link "Description"}).


 SAME EXTENTIONS IN ALL DIRECTORY/DEVICE CHOICES.

  You will be asked to choose via a requestor, the first device or
 directory that you want to search down through sub directories for the
 different types of file extentions. Once done, click on ok. 
 
  It will present you with the requestor again. 
 
  If you want to select another device or directory, you may do so and click
 on ok again. This can be done as many times as you like; with in reason.
 (Limit is 999 chioces)
  These choices are added to the main contents window of your new guide along
 with the extention type buttons for each dir or device.

  You can select assigns, but notice that the next requestor takes you out of
 the assign when you choose parent. (If you have Requestchoice, then parent
 will be choosen automatically for you. AskEnv spits the dummy on this for
 some reason.)
  There is not much that can be done about this. Sorry, you will have
 to go back to the Device/Assign list and choose it again manually, to do
 another directory inside the assign.

  After you have finished selecting the directories to search, and the
 next requestor appears, click on cancel and you will then be asked if your
 selections are correct or if you wish to redo them. (Check the correct
 selections in the Progress window.)
 


  Next you will be presented with another GUI window to set up your
 extention selections and settings.


 @{b}"Extention type" "By requestor"@{ub}

  You can type the extention in manually (it must begin with a "." as
 in ".Doc", or you can select it "By Requestor". Just select any file with
 the correct extention, and the script will get and store its extention type
 after you have clicked on STORE.

  Only one or the other needs an entry. If you enter both, the manual entry
 will get precidence. To use the requestor, click on the button called "By
 requestor", and a requestor will appear.

 @{b}NOTE: You may use Dos wildcards if you wish in the manual entry but the "."
 before the extention must be supplied! You may also do multiple searches
 for just one extention list using the OR wildcard switch. You must supply the
 enclosing brackets !!! i.e-

 (.doc|.readme|.guide)

  (If you do not know what the character "|" OR switch is. It can be entered
 by pressing the shift key and the backward-slash key "\")@{ub}

  The script will detect the multiple search and check that the first entry
 has a "." infront of it, but not the rest. (Just to check that you are
 putting it in) If you make a mistake in one of the others, say "guide"
 instead of ".guide" then the script will list all files ending in guide
 which will do the same job, but some may not be actual guides!


  @{b}"ALL Extention files?"@{ub}

  This over rides the "Extention Type" and "By requestor" entries.
 It forces the script to search for all extention files except #?.info
 icon files. The directory it is searching in should only contain simular
 extention files that can be loaded into a common Default tool. Other wise
 all sorts of things could happen, including crashing the machine when the
 file button is clicked on in the finished guide!

  The search pattern it uses to ignore icons is-

 .~(info|#?.info)

  The script will allow you to select more extention types for that directory,
 but is pretty pointless since they will all be listed by the first one.

  However! You may want several identical lists but which have different
 Default tools to do different things with the extention files for instance.
 This is generally handled by the Extra Button Tool, but you may want more
 than two Default tools for each file.
   There is also no point in turning the "Directory ALL" list option on for this
 guide, even though you can. The same goes for "THE WORKS!" list, but they are
 available if you want them!


  @{b}"Default tool"@{ub}

 The script will then need a default tool to be assigned to that extention
 list. For instance:

  .IFF extentions may be given the default tool VIEWT, which is a PD picture
 displaying program.

  .DOC files can be given the default tool MuchMore, a smooth scrolling PD
 text viewer.

  The path and name can be typed in manually or click on the button "Default
 tool" to use a requestor. By default, the requestor loads up the Utilities
 directory where most of these tools are stored, but you can select the tool
 from anywhere you like. Obviously the default tool for each extention must be
 able to load and do something with that file extention type, or the file
 button in the guide will fail to work. 

  Arguments for the default Tool can be typed into the manual entry, though
 they may not always work depending on how fussy the AmigaGuide program is.

 For instance to use MultiPlay to play song moduals, you would enter-

 C:MultiPlayer Play

 -the argument "Play" tells Multiplayer that it is being given an individual
 song modual rather than a play list, and to play it immediately. Hippo Player
 is better for playing your Mods through a Guide. (MultiPlayer has to be closed
 before playing the next song, where as Hippo will automatically load the next
 modual when it is called twice.)


 @{b}NOTE: There must not be any spaces in the file name or its path, nor for
 the default tool and its path!!@{ub}

 
  @{b}"Index name"@{ub}

  If you have choosen Customised Index Button names, the script will want a
 button name for that extention list to appear in the main index list.
 (By default it is just the extention eg. ".Doc". You could rename that to
 "Documents" instead for that extention list)

 NOTE: If you do not type anything in the box, it will be set to the extention
 name by default anyway!!


  @{b}"Sorted lists"@{ub}

  The check box for Sorted lists allows you to have your main extention lists
 sorted by file name, or sorted by subdirectories (if there are any) as
 read off the disk. (This may not be in alphabetical order in the
 subdirectory. Sorry, no way around that one i'm afraid, its the order the 
 Dos LIST command finds them in.).

  @{b}"Do you want an Extra button tool for this extention"@{ub}

  If you have asked for an Extra button tool, the setup will appear at the
 bottom of the requestor. However if you do not want one for a particular
 extention, you can uncheck this box and this extention will not get one!


 @{b}"Default tool"@{ub}

  Again, if you have asked for an extra button for each extention
 type, it will want a tool for that button. You can type its path and name
 manually or use a requestor. (Default is the DMCR tool S:ExtDMCR script.)

 This tool can also have arguments, but like the main tool it also must not
 have any spaces in the tools path or file name!


 @{b}"Button name"@{ub}
 This is the name of the button for the Extra button tool, Default is DMCR,
 however if you are not using the DMCR tool, it would be more apropriate to
 use something else like "Edit" or the name of the Tool like "CygnusEd" if
 that is what you are using.
 

 Once you are happy with all the settings, click on STORE.



  The script will then ask you for the next extention type. You can choose
 up to 999 extentions and their associated data. Each can have its own
 default tool, button name, extra button tool and name, default tool etc.
 The limit is more your RAM size really for the final size of the guide
 that you can read!


  When you are finished, click CANCEL in the next GUI that appears for the
 next extention and the script will then search for your choices and finally,
 the guide will be assembled and put in its new home and name.

 
 SEPARATE EXTENTIONS FOR EACH DIRECTORY

 This one works much the same as for the previous one, except the order of
 selection is different. 

 After you select a directory to search, the script will immediately ask
 you for the extention types to look for, for that directory only. 

 Once you have finished, select cancel when it asks for the next extention,
 and you will be asked for the next directory to search.

  It will then ask you for the extentions for that directory, and so on.
 You can look for as many different extention types in each directory
 choice as you like.

 Finally when you have done all the directories and their extentions, and
 it asks for another directory, select cancel and the search will start and
 the guide will be put together.
 
  To tidy up the contents page, the script works out the size of the biggest
 index name and then adds spaces to the other Button names to make them
 the same length; centered of course. :)

 @{b} The ALL and  WORKS! lists are created automatically if you have choosen
 them to be added. You do not have to choose all of the directories again to
 make them. @{ub}

@ENDNODE

@NODE "AutoScripts" 


 The Created AutoScript
 ----------------------
 
  In the RAM: disk will be an "AutoScript" which is a self contained script
 to up date your guide automatically. Each Guide you make, gets its own
 AutoScript!
 
 Copy the autoscript anywhere you like, rename it to what you like, and execute
 it whenever you wish to update your new guide. This is incase you have added
 more extention files etc or deleted them, and you wish to update the Guide to
 show these changes.

  This saves you reselecting everything manually all the time. When ever you
 wish to update that particular guides Extention list, execute the autoscript.
 It will re-search your selections and replace the old guide with an updated
 one. Complete with all of your original settings!

  That is, provided the old one is still where you originally told the script
 to put it and still has the same name. Other wise it will simply create a new
 guide where the old one use to be.

  The autoscript will update the guide, but not the icon. That is why you can
 put the autoscripts where you like once they have been created. They do not
 need to be in the ExtLister drawer to find an Icon for the guide. The guide
 should have been given one already by the original ExtentionLister script
 at creation.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "Generated Guides"
 
 
                 The generated AmigaGuide file:
                 ------------------------------
 
  The main contents window will have a list of all the devices and directories
 you selected along with the extention buttons for each. These take you to the
 lists of extention files found in each directory and consequent sub
 directories.

  If you asked for a DirAll list, it is a compiled list of all of the
 extentions lists for just that device or directory, combined into one. This
 is so you can find a file alphabetically if you do not know its extention,
 but know which partition or directory its in.


 If asked for, "THE WORKS!" button will take you to a combined list of
 everything listed in the guide in one large list, sorted by file name!

 
  I usually only have my four harddrive partitions in the main window as
 well as the DirALL and THE WORKS! to find all of my documents for instance.
  That way I can easily find the file extention I want anywhere on my hard
 drive by choosing the most appropriate list.

  If you have choosen the default tool scripts ExtCopy or ExtMove, the
 script will put a reset button for the Copy Destination or the
 MoveDestination at the top of the extention file list. You must enter them
 as S:ExtCopy or S:ExtMove when selecting the default tool, or the script
 will not recognise them! SYS:s/ExtCopy will not be detected for instance!
 See @{"Manual install of S: Scripts" link "Instalation"} for explanation of S: Dir scripts.

 
  There is a SEARCH feature for each guide. Clicking on search loads the
 script out of the S: dir called ExtListerSearch which will ask you for a
 string to look for. It will then list any buttons that match the string
 in a new separate guide and allow you to click on the file buttons as normal.

 The Search Guide will be loaded and displayed the moment it is finished!

  It also has a check box for the position of the string file in the search.
 With the tick on, the string can be any part of the file or extention name.
 i.e if "re" is entered, any file containing the letters "re" anywhere in its
 file name will be listed. The search is not case sensitive.
  With the check off, the search will look for file names begining with the
 string given- only. i.e. only files begining with "re" You can add wild cards
 but note that the search normally adds these either side of the string-

 #?re#?

 - Though you may like to put r#?e which the script will see as-

 #?r#?e#?

 This will find any file names that have a r followed by an e somewhere in
 the file name.

 It is not case sensitive!

  The search also multitasks, so you can continue to look around the guide
 as normal while the search is in progress. If the search is rather
 general, then it may take a while.
  Like asking it to find everything with the letter "a" in it. The time taken 
 is not the search itself, but rather the sorting of the list afterwards that
 takes most of the time. The shorter the list it finds, the quicker the
 search is! This is prolonged by the fact that there are identical buttons
 if there are DirALL lists, THE WORKS list and ExtALL lists.

  These extra buttons make the list up to four times longer than need be and
 have to be sorted and then removed and this is what makes the search slow!

  ED does the removal very quickly of the identical buttons in the search
 list. (....and you thought that ED was useless!.....) It would be nice to
 shut it up though and not open a window, however all attempts to stop this
 have failed dismally. Sorry!

  The finished search Guide, once produced, will remain in RAM: in case you
 wish to keep it. It will be overwritten at the next search.

 Note- it is not given an icon!!
 
@ENDNODE


@NODE "Aminet Lister"


                       AminetCDLister
                       --------------

   Creation
   --------

  This one works much the same as the ExtLister scripts, but are for
 Aminet CD's.

 @{b}"Sorted Readme lists"@{ub}

  The first option "Sorted Readme lists" determines wether the
 subdirectory readmes are sorted alphabetically by file name, or left sorted
 by directory as is read straight off the CD. I prefer them unsorted myself,
 leaving them sorted by sub directory!

 @{b}"ALL Readme"@{ub}
  
  The next option allows you to add an "ALL Readme" list to the guide.
 Every single readme from your selected directories are listed and sorted
 alpahbetically. This makes a full listing of one complete CD very large!
 (Like THE WORKS! option on Extlister)

 Aminet6 for instance: full listing.

 Normal version
 1.6 meg of Ram to make guide.
 Final guide=625k

 ALL ReadMe version
 3.43 meg of Ram to make guide.
 Final guide=1.57 meg
   
 @{b}"Copy Files" "Destination"@{ub}

  The next option is for a copy button instead of the Unpack button. If you
 like to simply copy your files to a destination and unpack them later, then
 this is the option for you! The Destination requestor button lets you
 specify where to copy the files to. (It will copy the main file and the
 ReadMe file to this destination) Default is RAM:

 @{b}"Path/File in Lists"@{ub}

  This cycle gadget allows you to have the path and file name of each readme
 listed, just the path, or nothing at all in the Readme lists. This is there
 more to cut down on the size of each guide. Just the path would be the best
 allround choice.
 
 @{b}"Default viewing tool"@{ub}

  You can then select a default viewing tool for the readmes and indexes.
 I suggest MUCHMORE (Default) as it loads the start of the file and views it 
 immediately. This is helpful for when you look at the main index. You don't
 have to wait until the whole file is loaded to start looking at it.  
 
 @{b}"Guides Name" "Path"@{ub}

  You then need select a name for the new Guide, and a destination. A
 destination is specified because creating a full listing of one of these CD's
 takes a lot of memory. Selecting the destination allows the final part, the
 actual guide to be done to disk, saving a little space in Ram. Unlike the
 ExtLister Guides, these can be moved, but not renamed, or the search functions
 will not work. (There is no AutoScript for these cos they never change :)
 
 @{b}"No RAM: Path"@{ub}

  Although the guide can be made to disk, the sorting routines and tempory
 holding of data are normally done in RAM: which can still use a lot of
 memory. This requestor allows you to specify a device like a harddrive where
 all of this can be done and make minimal use the RAM: disk! (only for
 variables)


 When you are happy with your selections, click on OK.

   You are then asked to select which directories you want to list. The
 order that you choose will be the order they appear in the main contents
 window. You can choose as many or few as you wish.

  (You may not want to list the Mods dir for example, if you are only interested
 in the utilities dir. Or vice versa if you are only interested in Mods.
  You can select as many dirs as you like to do the whole listing, or just
 the ones you are interested in.)

  You can also select across CDs. For instance you may want a listing of all
 of the utilities dirs across all of your aminet CD's, done in one guide. Or
 all of the Mods dirs across all of your Aminet CDs.

@{b} IMPORTANT @{ub}
  When changing CD's to select the next disc, go back to the Volumes list and
 make sure that you re-enter via the correct VOLUME NAME!! Do not just use CD0:
 or the guide will not be able to tell which CD to load from later. If you go
 in via CD0: the guide will try and read the file off which ever CD is in the
 CDROM at the time and an error will occur if it is the wrong one!

  (I find it easiest to put the new CD in and just change the number of the
 volume name manually in the requestor. Press return and it will list the
 new CD.)
 
  Once you have finished selecting your directories, click on cancel when it
 asks for another selection. The Script will then search down through all
 sub dirs in your selection and assemble the guide.
  If you have selected multiple CDs. The script will ask for them back,
 inturn, to search them. Sorry, it just has to be done that way to get
 things in the correct order.

  Aminet Guides generated can be very large, but they compress up to 90% !!!
 If you use something like ARCHandler, you can keep them compressed and
 read them through this. Aminet6.Guide compresses from 1.5 meg down to
 137 k for instance. Thus you can easily store these guides on your
 harddrive for your whole Aminet CD collection. You still need a fair amount
 of memory to uncrunch them and use them though!
  
 
@ENDNODE

@NODE "GAG"



                     Completed Aminet guide
                     ----------------------

  On the top line are two search buttons. One does a search of the guide its
 self and is multitasking. Because it searches the guide, it does not hog
 the CD, so while you are waiting, you can continue to look through the
 index's and readmes, or unpack files off the CD.

  The second search button searches the mainindex for the CD. This
 index has short file notes about the LHA files. The search will find any
 occurances of the string you specify in these file notes as well as the
 file name and is quite useful to find subject matter.

 NOTE: This search will look at the index of what ever Aminet CD is currently
 in CD0: If it is not an Aminet CD, then an error will occur.

  If the File only check box is selected, the search will only look at the
 start of each line in the index which happens to be the file name. It does
 not look for the string anywhere in the file notes- the start of the string
 must match the start of the files name.  
 
 All lines containing the string are put in a file and displayed automaticaly
 by C:MUCMORE when it is done. You will have to edit the ExtAmiIndex script in
 the S: dir to get a different viewer if you do not like MuchMore.

  This search will hog the CD as it reads the main index direct. You can how
 ever, still continue to use the guide. You can get things off the CD during
 this process, but this may result in a bit of disk thrashing and slow the
 search down.
 
  Neither searches give you any direct output of progress. The search files
 in S: have fairly extensive error trapping and will warn you if something
 is wrong. Otherwise, you will have to just wait, as these searches can take
 a while if the string is quite general.
  Both search files, once produced, will remain in RAM: in case you wish to
 keep them. They will be overwritten at the next search. Neither have
 icons.
 

  Each guide has a listing of "Indexes" and "Readmes" for each directory 
 selection you make. The Readme lists are not listed into their full
 directories. If you select the Utilities directory, then every readme from
 all of the sub directories in Utilities will be in just one list. They are
 not sorted unless you select that option. Thus they are in alphabetical order
 in each sub dir, but not in overall alpahbetical order.

  The index lists though, do have individual buttons for each index for each
 sub directory.
 
  I normally load up the appropriate sub-index in MuchMore for example, and
 then switch screens from MuchMore to the approprate part of the readme list
 in the guide to get the full readme (If it looks interesting enough from the
 brief description in the Index file.) 

  If the full readme describes what I want to a tee, I then hit the "unpack"
 or the "Copy" button and the file is unpacked to RAM: or copied to my
 destination for me. The copy output is very brief, more to show you
 something is happening than anything else.

 The extra directories just make it more painful!
  If you want the full directory structure, it will have to be done in the
 main contents window of the guide. Heck- you may as well look at the CD
 direct if you want the full dir structure! The main benefit here is to
 list the Index's easily instead of having to look for them and then copy or
 unpack the files automatically.

 If you are using the unpack button, and the file is not a #?.LHA file, the
 ExtAmi script will try to load the file into an apropriate tool. For
 instance, if it is a Jpeg picture, it will be loaded into VT (ViewTech
 picture viewer).See @{"Manual install of S: Scripts" link "Instalation"} for explanation
 of the ExtAmi script and its installation.  
  
  At the bottom of the guide is an ALL list of "Indexes" with their path; and
 a "Main Index" button to load up the main index file and read it.
 
 If there are multiple selections of CD's or not, the "Main Index button" and
 the "Search Main Index", will simply search the current CD in CD0:
 regardless.
 If it is not a Aminet CD in CD0: an error will be reported.


@ENDNODE
 
